Education and education may have substantial effects on issues of social inequality. On the one hand, education has the ability to lessen existing social and structural inequalities by equipping people with the information, skills, and talents necessary to participate in society and enhance their social and economic standing. Education may also enhance social mobility and allow people to escape cycles of poverty and disadvantage. On the other side, education may also reproduce social and economic inequality, therefore perpetuating existing social and structural inequalities. This may occur in a variety of ways: Access to instruction: Social and economic inequality may be perpetuated when marginalized and disadvantaged groups have limited access to education. This may occur when schools are underfunded, lack resources, or are situated in areas where poverty and violence are prevalent. Curriculum and instruction: The curriculum and instruction in schools may perpetuate social and economic inequality by failing to educate pupils with the information, skills, and talents required to operate in society, or by presenting a limited and biased view of history and culture. This may occur if the curriculum is not culturally sensitive and relevant, or if it is not adapted to the requirements of various student groups. Tracking and streaming: Tracking and streaming systems may perpetuate social and economic inequality by classifying pupils into various academic programs depending on their perceived aptitude. This may result in the placement of students from marginalized and disadvantaged groups in lower-level classrooms and the denial of access to advanced programs and opportunities. Teachers' prejudices that restrict the potential of pupils from marginalized and disadvantaged groups may perpetuate social and economic injustice. This may occur when instructors have low expectations for some children or fail to provide them the same chances and assistance as other pupils. In conclusion, education and schooling may have substantial effects on issues of social inequality. Education has the ability to eliminate existing social and structural inequalities, but it also has the capacity to perpetuate them. It is essential to acknowledge the ways in which education may perpetuate social and economic inequality and to strive toward developing a more equitable education system that encourages social mobility and gives equal opportunity to all students. 